---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Fluid Mechanics &amp; Hydraulics · Virtual Labs · AquinTutor" description="Bernoulli, Reynolds, pipe friction, venturi and orifice flow — live apparatus with real fluid physics.">

<style>
  body { background: #070a0d; color: #e8eef2; margin: 0; }
  .fz-wrap { max-width: 1360px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 24px 4vw 80px; }
  .fz-back { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11px; color: #8ea2ad; text-decoration: none; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .fz-back:hover { color: #38bdf8; }
  .fz-eye { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.18em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #38bdf8; font-weight: 700; }
  .fz-title { font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 38px; font-weight: 600; margin: 4px 0 6px; letter-spacing: -0.02em; line-height: 1.1; }
  .fz-title em { color: #38bdf8; font-style: italic; font-weight: 500; }
  .fz-sub { color: #8ea2ad; max-width: 840px; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.55; margin: 0 0 22px; }

  .fz-shell { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 274px minmax(0,1fr); gap: 18px; }
  @media (max-width: 960px) { .fz-shell { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

  .fz-exp-list { background: #0d1318; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; border-radius: 12px; padding: 10px; align-self: start; position: sticky; top: 14px; }
  .fz-exp-list h4 { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.16em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #5eead4; font-weight: 700; margin: 6px 8px 10px; }
  .fz-exp { display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 9px; width: 100%; text-align: left; background: transparent; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 8px; color: #c4d2da; font-family: inherit; padding: 9px 10px; cursor: pointer; margin-bottom: 2px; }
  .fz-exp:hover { background: #111921; }
  .fz-exp.active { background: rgba(56,189,248,0.10); border-color: #38bdf8; }
  .fz-exp .num { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; color: #38bdf8; flex: 0 0 auto; width: 18px; }
  .fz-exp .nm { font-size: 12.5px; line-height: 1.3; }
  .fz-exp.active .nm { color: #fff; }

  .fz-bench { min-width: 0; }
  .fz-exp-head { font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 26px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 4px; color: #fff; }
  .fz-exp-tag { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #38bdf8; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 14px; }

  .fz-tabs { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 4px; margin-bottom: 18px; border-bottom: 1px solid #16212a; }
  .fz-tab { background: transparent; border: none; border-bottom: 2px solid transparent; color: #8ea2ad; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10.5px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 9px 12px; cursor: pointer; }
  .fz-tab:hover { color: #c4d2da; }
  .fz-tab.active { color: #38bdf8; border-bottom-color: #38bdf8; }

  .fz-sec { display: none; }
  .fz-sec.active { display: block; }

  .fz-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 308px minmax(0,1fr); gap: 18px; }
  @media (max-width: 820px) { .fz-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

  .fz-panel { background: #0d1318; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; border-radius: 12px; padding: 16px; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .fz-panel h3 { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.16em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #38bdf8; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 12px; }

  .fz-ctl { display: grid; gap: 5px; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .fz-ctl label { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: #92a6b3; font-weight: 700; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; }
  .fz-ctl label span { color: #38bdf8; }
  .fz-ctl input[type=range] { width: 100%; accent-color: #38bdf8; }
  .fz-ctl select { width: 100%; background: #070a0d; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; color: #fff; padding: 7px 10px; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 12px; font-family: inherit; }

  .fz-seg { display: flex; gap: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .fz-seg button { flex: 1; background: #070a0d; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; color: #8ea2ad; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.05em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 8px 6px; border-radius: 5px; cursor: pointer; }
  .fz-seg button.on { background: rgba(56,189,248,0.12); border-color: #38bdf8; color: #38bdf8; }

  .fz-btn { width: 100%; background: #38bdf8; color: #04161f; border: none; border-radius: 7px; padding: 9px 12px; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10.5px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; cursor: pointer; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .fz-btn:hover { background: #7dd3fc; }
  .fz-btn.ghost { background: transparent; color: #c4d2da; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; }
  .fz-btn.ghost:hover { border-color: #38bdf8; color: #38bdf8; }

  .fz-metric { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto; gap: 8px; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11.5px; padding: 5px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #131e26; }
  .fz-metric:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .fz-metric-l { color: #92a6b3; }
  .fz-metric-v { color: #38bdf8; font-weight: 700; text-align: right; }
  .fz-metric-v.amber { color: #fbbf24; }
  .fz-metric-v.green { color: #5eead4; }
  .fz-metric-v.red { color: #fca5a5; }
  .fz-metric-v.purple { color: #c4b5fd; }

  .fz-svg, .fz-cv { width: 100%; background: #070a0d; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; border-radius: 10px; display: block; }
  .fz-formula { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 12px; color: #c4d2da; line-height: 1.7; background: #070a0d; border: 1px solid #16212a; border-radius: 8px; padding: 12px 14px; margin-top: 4px; }
  .fz-formula b { color: #fbbf24; }
  .fz-note { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 10px; color: #66788a; line-height: 1.6; margin-top: 8px; }
  .fz-plots { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; }
  @media (max-width: 720px) { .fz-plots { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }

  .fz-prose { background: #0d1318; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px 22px; max-width: 900px; }
  .fz-prose p { color: #c0cdd6; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 14px; }
  .fz-prose ol { color: #c0cdd6; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 22px; margin: 0; }
  .fz-prose ol li { margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .fz-prose .eqs { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 12.5px; color: #38bdf8; line-height: 1.9; background: #070a0d; border: 1px solid #16212a; border-radius: 8px; padding: 14px 16px; margin: 4px 0 16px; }
  .fz-prose .eqs b { color: #fbbf24; }
  .fz-prose .refs { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; }
  .fz-prose .refs li { font-size: 12.5px; color: #92a6b3; line-height: 1.55; padding: 7px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #131e26; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; }
  .fz-prose .refs li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }

  .fz-quiz { max-width: 860px; }
  .fz-q { background: #0d1318; border: 1px solid #1d2a33; border-radius: 12px; padding: 16px 18px; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .fz-q .qhead { font-size: 14px; color: #fff; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 12px; line-height: 1.5; }
  .fz-q .qhead .qn { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; color: #fbbf24; font-size: 12px; margin-right: 8px; }
  .fz-opt { display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 9px; padding: 9px 11px; border: 1px solid #182530; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 7px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 13px; color: #c0cdd6; }
  .fz-opt:hover { border-color: #2b3d49; background: #111921; }
  .fz-opt input { accent-color: #38bdf8; margin-top: 2px; }
  .fz-opt.correct { border-color: #5eead4; background: rgba(94,234,212,0.10); color: #d2f7ef; }
  .fz-opt.wrong { border-color: #fca5a5; background: rgba(252,165,165,0.08); color: #f5d6d6; }
  .fz-expl { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.55; margin-top: 8px; padding: 9px 11px; border-radius: 7px; display: none; }
  .fz-expl.show { display: block; }
  .fz-expl.ok { color: #5eead4; background: rgba(94,234,212,0.07); border: 1px solid rgba(94,234,212,0.2); }
  .fz-expl.no { color: #fca5a5; background: rgba(252,165,165,0.07); border: 1px solid rgba(252,165,165,0.2); }
  .fz-check { background: #38bdf8; color: #04161f; border: none; border-radius: 7px; padding: 9px 18px; font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; cursor: pointer; margin-top: 4px; }
  .fz-check:hover { background: #7dd3fc; }
  .fz-score { font-family: 'Geist Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 12px; color: #fbbf24; margin-left: 14px; font-weight: 700; }
</style>

<main class="fz-wrap">
  <a href="/aquintutor/labs" class="fz-back">
    <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" fill="none"><path d="M19 12H5M12 19l-7-7 7-7"/></svg>
    Back to Labs
  </a>
  <div class="fz-eye">Lab &middot; Fluid Mechanics &amp; Hydraulics</div>
  <h1 class="fz-title">Flow, pressure &amp; <em>hydraulic</em> machines.</h1>
  <p class="fz-sub">Six working benches in the IIT Virtual Labs format. Pick an experiment, read its aim, theory and procedure, then drive the live apparatus &mdash; every slider re-solves the underlying fluid mechanics from continuity, Bernoulli, Reynolds and Darcy-Weisbach &mdash; and test yourself with the self-assessment.</p>

  <div class="fz-shell">
    <aside class="fz-exp-list" id="expList">
      <h4>Experiments</h4>
      <button class="fz-exp active" data-exp="bern"><span class="num">1</span><span class="nm">Bernoulli &amp; continuity in a varying pipe</span></button>
      <button class="fz-exp" data-exp="reyn"><span class="num">2</span><span class="nm">Reynolds: laminar vs turbulent flow</span></button>
      <button class="fz-exp" data-exp="fric"><span class="num">3</span><span class="nm">Pipe friction &amp; head loss (Darcy-Weisbach)</span></button>
      <button class="fz-exp" data-exp="vent"><span class="num">4</span><span class="nm">Venturi / orifice flow meter</span></button>
      <button class="fz-exp" data-exp="torr"><span class="num">5</span><span class="nm">Orifice discharge &amp; tank draining</span></button>
      <button class="fz-exp" data-exp="mano"><span class="num">6</span><span class="nm">Hydrostatic pressure &amp; manometer</span></button>
    </aside>

    <div class="fz-bench">

      <!-- ============== EXPERIMENT 1: BERNOULLI ============== -->
      <section class="fz-experiment active" data-exp="bern">
        <h2 class="fz-exp-head">Bernoulli &amp; continuity in a varying-area pipe</h2>
        <div class="fz-exp-tag">Experiment 1 &middot; Energy &amp; mass conservation</div>
        <div class="fz-tabs">
          <button class="fz-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="fz-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Fluid</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><select id="be_fluid"></select></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Geometry &amp; flow</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Inlet diameter D1 (cm) <span id="be_D1V">10.0</span></label><input id="be_D1" type="range" min="4" max="16" step="0.2" value="10"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Throat diameter D2 (cm) <span id="be_D2V">5.0</span></label><input id="be_D2" type="range" min="2" max="16" step="0.2" value="5"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Volume flow Q (L/s) <span id="be_QV">8.0</span></label><input id="be_Q" type="range" min="1" max="40" step="0.5" value="8"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Throat height z2 above inlet (m) <span id="be_zV">0.0</span></label><input id="be_z" type="range" min="-1.5" max="1.5" step="0.05" value="0"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Inlet gauge pressure p1 (kPa) <span id="be_pV">120</span></label><input id="be_p" type="range" min="30" max="300" step="5" value="120"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Continuity</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Area A1</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="be_A1">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Area A2 (throat)</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="be_A2">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Velocity v1</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="be_v1">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Velocity v2 (throat)</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="be_v2">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Area ratio A1/A2</span><span class="fz-metric-v purple" id="be_ar">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Bernoulli</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Throat pressure p2</span><span class="fz-metric-v red" id="be_p2">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Pressure drop p1-p2</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="be_dp">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Total head H</span><span class="fz-metric-v green" id="be_H">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Cavitation risk</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="be_cav">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Converging-diverging pipe with piezometer tubes</h3>
                <canvas id="be_cv" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="380"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-note">Particles advect at the local velocity (continuity: they speed up through the throat). Piezometer column height = static pressure head p / rho g; the throat column drops as the flow accelerates.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-plots">
                <div class="fz-panel" style="margin:0;">
                  <h3>Head distribution along the pipe (m)</h3>
                  <canvas id="be_head" class="fz-cv" width="380" height="240"></canvas>
                </div>
                <div class="fz-panel" style="margin:0;">
                  <h3>Energy grade line &amp; hydraulic grade line</h3>
                  <canvas id="be_egl" class="fz-cv" width="380" height="240"></canvas>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="fz-prose"><p>To verify the continuity equation and Bernoulli's energy equation for the steady, incompressible flow of a fluid through a converging-diverging pipe, and to demonstrate that where the cross-section narrows the velocity rises and the static pressure falls.</p></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="fz-prose">
          <p>For steady incompressible flow the mass flow rate is the same at every section, so the volume flow Q = A&middot;v is constant: a smaller area must carry a faster velocity. Bernoulli's equation expresses conservation of mechanical energy per unit weight along a streamline &mdash; the sum of pressure head, velocity head and elevation head is constant for an ideal (frictionless) fluid.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            Continuity:&nbsp; <b>A1 v1 = A2 v2 = Q</b><br/>
            Bernoulli:&nbsp; <b>p1/(rho g) + v1^2/(2g) + z1 = p2/(rho g) + v2^2/(2g) + z2</b><br/>
            Therefore:&nbsp; p1 - p2 = (rho/2)(v2^2 - v1^2) + rho g (z2 - z1)
          </div>
          <p>At a 2:1 area reduction (A2 = A1/2) the velocity doubles (v2 = 2 v1) and the pressure head falls by (v2^2 - v1^2)/2g = 3 v1^2 / 2g. If the throat pressure approaches the vapour pressure of the liquid, cavitation can occur.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="fz-prose"><ol>
          <li>Choose the working fluid and set the inlet and throat diameters.</li>
          <li>Set the volume flow rate Q; observe the particles speed up through the throat.</li>
          <li>Read the velocities v1 and v2 and confirm A1 v1 = A2 v2 = Q.</li>
          <li>Read the throat pressure p2 from Bernoulli and compare the piezometer column heights.</li>
          <li>Raise the flow until the cavitation indicator warns that p2 nears the vapour pressure.</li>
          <li>Tilt the throat elevation z2 and watch the elevation-head term shift the energy line.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="fz-quiz" data-quiz="bern"></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="fz-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>F. M. White, Fluid Mechanics, 8th ed., McGraw-Hill, Ch. 3 (Bernoulli equation).</li>
          <li>B. R. Munson et al., Fundamentals of Fluid Mechanics, Wiley, Ch. 3.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs &mdash; Fluid Mechanics: Bernoulli's Theorem, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============== EXPERIMENT 2: REYNOLDS ============== -->
      <section class="fz-experiment" data-exp="reyn">
        <h2 class="fz-exp-head">Reynolds experiment: laminar vs turbulent flow</h2>
        <div class="fz-exp-tag">Experiment 2 &middot; Flow regimes</div>
        <div class="fz-tabs">
          <button class="fz-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="fz-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Fluid</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><select id="re_fluid"></select></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Tube &amp; flow</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Tube diameter D (mm) <span id="re_DV">15.0</span></label><input id="re_D" type="range" min="4" max="40" step="0.5" value="15"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Mean velocity v (m/s) <span id="re_vV">0.20</span></label><input id="re_v" type="range" min="0.01" max="3" step="0.01" value="0.2"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Temperature (deg C) <span id="re_TV">20</span></label><input id="re_T" type="range" min="5" max="90" step="1" value="20"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Results</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Density rho</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="re_rho">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Viscosity mu</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="re_mu">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Reynolds number Re</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="re_Re">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Flow regime</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="re_reg">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Volume flow Q</span><span class="fz-metric-v green" id="re_Q">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Critical velocity</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">v at Re = 2300</span><span class="fz-metric-v purple" id="re_vc">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-note" style="margin-top:8px;color:#5eead4;">Re &lt; 2300 laminar &middot; 2300-4000 transitional &middot; &gt; 4000 turbulent</div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Glass tube with dye filament (Reynolds apparatus)</h3>
                <canvas id="re_cv" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="340"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-note">A fine dye jet enters the tube. At low Re it stays a straight thread (laminar); near the critical value it wavers (transitional); at high Re it bursts and mixes across the tube (turbulent). The animation samples the live Re.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Velocity profile across the tube</h3>
                <canvas id="re_prof" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="180"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-formula">Laminar flow has a parabolic profile (Hagen-Poiseuille); turbulent flow has a flatter, fuller profile from cross-stream momentum mixing. <b>Re = rho v D / mu</b>.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="fz-prose"><p>To reproduce Osborne Reynolds' classic experiment &mdash; injecting a dye filament into flow through a glass tube &mdash; and to identify the laminar, transitional and turbulent regimes, relating the change of regime to the dimensionless Reynolds number.</p></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="fz-prose">
          <p>The Reynolds number is the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces in a flow. When viscous forces dominate (low Re) disturbances are damped and the flow is orderly and laminar; the dye stays a clean thread. When inertia dominates (high Re) small disturbances grow, the flow becomes chaotic and turbulent, and the dye mixes across the whole tube.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            <b>Re = rho v D / mu = v D / nu</b><br/>
            Laminar:&nbsp; Re &lt; 2300&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Transitional:&nbsp; 2300 to 4000&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Turbulent:&nbsp; Re &gt; 4000<br/>
            Critical velocity:&nbsp; v_c = Re_c &middot; mu / (rho D)
          </div>
          <p>Here rho and mu are taken at the chosen temperature; water's viscosity falls steeply as it warms, so the same velocity gives a higher Re in hot water.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="fz-prose"><ol>
          <li>Select the fluid and set the tube diameter.</li>
          <li>Start from a low velocity and watch the dye stay a straight filament (laminar).</li>
          <li>Raise the velocity until the thread begins to waver near Re = 2300 (transitional).</li>
          <li>Increase further until the dye disperses across the tube (turbulent, Re &gt; 4000).</li>
          <li>Change the temperature and note how the critical velocity shifts with viscosity.</li>
          <li>Compare the laminar parabolic profile with the fuller turbulent profile.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="fz-quiz" data-quiz="reyn"></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="fz-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>O. Reynolds, An Experimental Investigation, Phil. Trans. R. Soc., 1883.</li>
          <li>F. M. White, Fluid Mechanics, 8th ed., McGraw-Hill, Ch. 6 (Viscous flow in pipes).</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs &mdash; Fluid Mechanics: Reynolds Experiment, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============== EXPERIMENT 3: PIPE FRICTION ============== -->
      <section class="fz-experiment" data-exp="fric">
        <h2 class="fz-exp-head">Pipe friction &amp; head loss (Darcy-Weisbach)</h2>
        <div class="fz-exp-tag">Experiment 3 &middot; Major losses</div>
        <div class="fz-tabs">
          <button class="fz-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="fz-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Fluid</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><select id="fr_fluid"></select></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Pipe &amp; flow</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Diameter D (mm) <span id="fr_DV">50</span></label><input id="fr_D" type="range" min="10" max="150" step="1" value="50"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Length L (m) <span id="fr_LV">20</span></label><input id="fr_L" type="range" min="2" max="100" step="1" value="20"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Roughness e (mm) <span id="fr_eV">0.10</span></label><input id="fr_e" type="range" min="0" max="3" step="0.01" value="0.1"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Flow rate Q (L/s) <span id="fr_QV">5.0</span></label><input id="fr_Q" type="range" min="0.05" max="40" step="0.05" value="5"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Results</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Velocity v</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="fr_v">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Reynolds Re</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="fr_Re">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Relative roughness e/D</span><span class="fz-metric-v purple" id="fr_eD">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Friction factor f</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="fr_f">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Head loss hf</span><span class="fz-metric-v red" id="fr_hf">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Pressure drop</span><span class="fz-metric-v green" id="fr_dp">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Moody chart &middot; friction factor vs Reynolds number</h3>
                <canvas id="fr_moody" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="380"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-note">Log-log Moody diagram. The cross marks your operating point. Laminar uses f = 64/Re; turbulent uses the Swamee-Jain explicit form of the Colebrook equation for the chosen relative roughness.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Head loss vs flow rate</h3>
                <canvas id="fr_curve" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="220"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-formula"><b>hf = f (L/D)(v^2 / 2g)</b>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; laminar f = 64/Re&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; turbulent 1/sqrt(f) = -2 log10(e/3.7D + 2.51/(Re sqrt(f))) (Colebrook).</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="fz-prose"><p>To measure the major head loss due to friction in a uniform circular pipe as a function of flow rate, to determine the Darcy friction factor from the Reynolds number and relative roughness, and to locate the operating point on the Moody chart.</p></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="fz-prose">
          <p>As a real fluid flows through a pipe, wall shear dissipates mechanical energy; the lost energy per unit weight is the friction head loss. The Darcy-Weisbach equation relates this loss to the velocity head through a dimensionless friction factor f, which itself depends on the flow regime. In laminar flow f follows directly from the Hagen-Poiseuille solution; in turbulent flow it depends on both Reynolds number and the pipe's relative roughness, captured by the Colebrook equation (plotted as the Moody chart).</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            Darcy-Weisbach:&nbsp; <b>hf = f (L/D)(v^2 / 2g)</b><br/>
            Laminar (Re &lt; 2300):&nbsp; <b>f = 64 / Re</b><br/>
            Turbulent (Swamee-Jain):&nbsp; f = 0.25 / [log10(e/3.7D + 5.74/Re^0.9)]^2<br/>
            Pressure drop:&nbsp; dp = rho g hf
          </div>
          <p>Head loss grows roughly with the square of the velocity (and hence flow rate) in turbulent flow, so doubling the flow quadruples the loss.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="fz-prose"><ol>
          <li>Choose the fluid and set the pipe diameter, length and wall roughness.</li>
          <li>Set the flow rate Q; read the mean velocity and Reynolds number.</li>
          <li>Note whether the flow is laminar or turbulent and which friction-factor law applies.</li>
          <li>Read the friction factor and the resulting Darcy-Weisbach head loss.</li>
          <li>Locate the operating point on the Moody chart and follow it as Q changes.</li>
          <li>Increase the roughness and observe f rise toward its fully-rough plateau.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="fz-quiz" data-quiz="fric"></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="fz-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>L. F. Moody, Friction Factors for Pipe Flow, Trans. ASME, 1944.</li>
          <li>P. K. Swamee &amp; A. K. Jain, Explicit equations for pipe-flow problems, J. Hydraulics Div., 1976.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs &mdash; Fluid Mechanics: Friction in Pipes, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============== EXPERIMENT 4: VENTURI ============== -->
      <section class="fz-experiment" data-exp="vent">
        <h2 class="fz-exp-head">Venturi / orifice flow meter</h2>
        <div class="fz-exp-tag">Experiment 4 &middot; Differential-pressure metering</div>
        <div class="fz-tabs">
          <button class="fz-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="fz-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Meter type</h3>
                <div class="fz-seg" id="ve_type">
                  <button class="on" data-t="venturi">Venturi</button>
                  <button data-t="orifice">Orifice plate</button>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Geometry</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Pipe diameter D1 (mm) <span id="ve_D1V">100</span></label><input id="ve_D1" type="range" min="40" max="200" step="2" value="100"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Throat diameter D2 (mm) <span id="ve_D2V">50</span></label><input id="ve_D2" type="range" min="15" max="180" step="1" value="50"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Manometer fluid SG <span id="ve_sgV">13.6</span></label><input id="ve_sg" type="range" min="1.2" max="13.6" step="0.1" value="13.6"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Drive</h3>
                <div class="fz-seg" id="ve_drive">
                  <button class="on" data-d="dp">Set head dp</button>
                  <button data-d="q">Set flow Q</button>
                </div>
                <div class="fz-ctl" id="ve_dpwrap"><label>Manometer deflection h (mm) <span id="ve_hV">200</span></label><input id="ve_h" type="range" min="5" max="600" step="5" value="200"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl" id="ve_qwrap" style="display:none;"><label>Actual flow Q (L/s) <span id="ve_qV">10</span></label><input id="ve_q" type="range" min="0.5" max="60" step="0.5" value="10"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Results</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Beta = D2/D1</span><span class="fz-metric-v purple" id="ve_beta">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Discharge coeff. Cd</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="ve_cd">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Pressure diff p1-p2</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="ve_dp">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Ideal flow Q_ideal</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="ve_qi">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Actual flow Q</span><span class="fz-metric-v green" id="ve_qa">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Throat velocity v2</span><span class="fz-metric-v red" id="ve_v2">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Flow meter with differential manometer</h3>
                <canvas id="ve_cv" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="400"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-note">The constriction accelerates the flow and lowers its pressure; the U-tube manometer reads the head difference. Discharge is recovered from the deflection with the meter's discharge coefficient.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Calibration: discharge vs square-root of head</h3>
                <canvas id="ve_cal" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="200"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-formula"><b>Q = Cd A2 sqrt( 2 (p1-p2) / (rho (1 - (A2/A1)^2)) )</b>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; p1-p2 = (SG_m - 1) rho g h (mercury over water).</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="fz-prose"><p>To measure volume flow rate with a venturi or orifice-plate meter by reading the differential pressure across the constriction, to apply the meter equation, and to understand the role of the discharge coefficient that corrects the ideal Bernoulli flow for real losses.</p></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="fz-prose">
          <p>A flow meter creates a known constriction. Combining continuity with Bernoulli between the upstream pipe (1) and the throat (2) gives the ideal discharge in terms of the pressure difference. Real flow separates slightly and loses some energy, so the measured discharge is the ideal value multiplied by a discharge coefficient Cd. A venturi recovers most of its pressure and has Cd near 0.97-0.98; a sharp-edged orifice plate has stronger contraction (the vena contracta) and Cd near 0.6-0.65.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            From Bernoulli + continuity:&nbsp; <b>Q_ideal = A2 sqrt( 2 dp / (rho (1 - beta^4)) )</b>,&nbsp; beta = D2/D1<br/>
            Real discharge:&nbsp; <b>Q = Cd &middot; Q_ideal</b><br/>
            Manometer:&nbsp; dp = (SG_m - 1) rho_water g h
          </div>
          <p>Because Q is proportional to the square root of the head difference, a calibration plot of Q against sqrt(h) is a straight line through the origin.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="fz-prose"><ol>
          <li>Select the meter type (venturi or orifice plate) and set the pipe and throat diameters.</li>
          <li>Choose the manometer fluid (mercury for large flows, lighter fluids for small).</li>
          <li>Set the manometer deflection h, or switch to drive the actual flow Q directly.</li>
          <li>Read the pressure difference, the ideal and actual discharge, and the throat velocity.</li>
          <li>Compare the discharge coefficient of the venturi with that of the orifice plate.</li>
          <li>Confirm that Q rises with the square root of the head, giving a linear calibration.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="fz-quiz" data-quiz="vent"></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="fz-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>B. R. Munson et al., Fundamentals of Fluid Mechanics, Wiley, Ch. 8 (Flow measurement).</li>
          <li>ISO 5167 &mdash; Measurement of fluid flow by pressure differential devices.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs &mdash; Fluid Mechanics: Venturimeter &amp; Orifice meter, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============== EXPERIMENT 5: TORRICELLI ============== -->
      <section class="fz-experiment" data-exp="torr">
        <h2 class="fz-exp-head">Orifice discharge &amp; tank draining (Torricelli)</h2>
        <div class="fz-exp-tag">Experiment 5 &middot; Free jet &amp; falling head</div>
        <div class="fz-tabs">
          <button class="fz-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
          <button class="fz-tab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="fz-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Tank &amp; orifice</h3>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Tank cross-section A_t (m^2) <span id="to_AtV">0.50</span></label><input id="to_At" type="range" min="0.05" max="2" step="0.05" value="0.5"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Initial head H0 (m) <span id="to_HV">2.00</span></label><input id="to_H" type="range" min="0.3" max="5" step="0.1" value="2"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Orifice diameter d (mm) <span id="to_dV">30</span></label><input id="to_d" type="range" min="5" max="80" step="1" value="30"/></div>
                <div class="fz-ctl"><label>Discharge coeff. Cd <span id="to_cdV">0.62</span></label><input id="to_cd" type="range" min="0.5" max="1" step="0.01" value="0.62"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Run</h3>
                <button class="fz-btn" id="to_run">Open valve &amp; drain</button>
                <button class="fz-btn ghost" id="to_reset">Refill tank</button>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Live state</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Current head h</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="to_h">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Jet velocity v</span><span class="fz-metric-v amber" id="to_v">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Discharge Q</span><span class="fz-metric-v green" id="to_Q">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Horizontal range x</span><span class="fz-metric-v purple" id="to_x">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Elapsed time</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="to_t">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Theoretical</h3>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">v at full head</span><span class="fz-metric-v" id="to_v0">&mdash;</span></div>
                <div class="fz-metric"><span class="fz-metric-l">Time to empty</span><span class="fz-metric-v red" id="to_te">&mdash;</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Draining tank with free jet (side orifice)</h3>
                <canvas id="to_cv" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="420"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-note">The jet leaves at v = sqrt(2 g h) and follows a projectile path; as the head falls the jet slows and its range shortens. The water level drops at dh/dt = -Cd a sqrt(2 g h) / A_t.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fz-panel">
                <h3>Head vs time (draining curve)</h3>
                <canvas id="to_curve" class="fz-cv" width="760" height="200"></canvas>
                <div class="fz-formula"><b>v = sqrt(2 g h)</b> (Torricelli)&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Q = Cd a sqrt(2 g h)&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; time to empty t = (2 A_t / (Cd a sqrt(2g))) sqrt(H0).</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="fz-prose"><p>To study the discharge of a liquid through a sharp-edged orifice under a gravity head, to verify Torricelli's theorem for the jet velocity, to find the coefficient of discharge, and to compute the time taken to empty a draining tank.</p></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="fz-prose">
          <p>Applying Bernoulli between the free surface and the orifice (both at atmospheric pressure) gives the ideal efflux velocity Torricelli's theorem. Real jets contract at the vena contracta and lose a little energy, so the actual discharge is reduced by the coefficient of discharge Cd. As the tank drains, the head falls, the velocity decreases, and the level descends ever more slowly &mdash; the draining time follows by integrating the unsteady mass balance.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            Torricelli:&nbsp; <b>v = sqrt(2 g h)</b><br/>
            Discharge:&nbsp; <b>Q = Cd &middot; a &middot; sqrt(2 g h)</b>,&nbsp; a = orifice area<br/>
            Unsteady drain:&nbsp; A_t dh/dt = -Q&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp; t_empty = (2 A_t / (Cd a sqrt(2g))) sqrt(H0)<br/>
            Jet range (orifice at height y):&nbsp; x = 2 sqrt(h &middot; y)
          </div>
          <p>The simulation integrates dh/dt numerically each frame, so the live draining curve reproduces the closed-form sqrt(H0) emptying time.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="fz-prose"><ol>
          <li>Set the tank cross-section, the initial head and the orifice diameter.</li>
          <li>Set the coefficient of discharge (about 0.62 for a sharp-edged orifice).</li>
          <li>Press Open valve and watch the jet issue and the head fall.</li>
          <li>Observe the jet velocity following sqrt(2 g h) and its range shrinking as h drops.</li>
          <li>Read the time to empty and compare it with the theoretical sqrt(H0) law.</li>
          <li>Double the orifice area and confirm the emptying time roughly halves.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="fz-quiz" data-quiz="torr"></div></div>

        <div class="fz-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="fz-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>F. M. White, Fluid Mechanics, 8th ed., McGraw-Hill, Ch. 3 (Frictionless flow).</li>
          <li>R. K. Bansal, Fluid Mechanics and Hydraulic Machines, Laxmi, Ch. 8 (Orifices).</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs &mdash; Fluid Mechanics: Flow through an Orifice, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

